quran[15]{c,v,t,f}:
112,1,"Say: {1} “He is Allah, {2} the One and Unique; {3}",footnotes:1:That is
112,2,"Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need; {1}",footnotes:1:The word used in the original is samad of which the root is smd. A look at the derivatives in Arabic from this root will show how comprehensive and vast this word is in meaning. (Lexical discussion of the meanings of the derivatives is omitted).
112,3,"He neither begot any nor was He begotten, {1}",footnotes:1:The polytheists in every age have adopted the concept that like men
112,4,"and none is comparable to Him.” {1}",footnotes:1:The word kufu as used in the original means an example
113,1,"Say: {1} “I seek refuge {2} with the Lord of the rising day; {3}",footnotes:1:(1) The act of seeking refuge itself.As qul (say) is a part of the message which was conveyed to the Prophet (peace be upon him) by revelation for preaching his prophetic message
113,2,"from the evil of all that He created; {1}",footnotes:1:In other words: I seek His refuge from the evil of all creatures. A few things in this sentence deserve consideration.
113,3,"from the evil of night's darkness when it spreads around; {1}",footnotes:1:After seeking Allah’s refuge generally from the evil of the creatures
113,4,"from the evil of the women who blow on knots; {1}",footnotes:1:The word uqad in naffathat fil-uqad is plural of uqdah
113,5,"and from the evil of the envier when he envies.” {1}",footnotes:1:Hasad means that a person should feel unhappy at the better fortune
114,1,"Say: “I seek refuge with the Lord of mankind;"
114,2,"the King of mankind,"
114,3,"the True God of mankind, {1}",footnotes:1:Here also
114,4,"from the mischief of the whispering, elusive prompter who returns again and again, {1}",footnotes:1:The word waswas in waswas-il-khannas means the one who whispers over and over again
114,5,"who whispers in the hearts of people;"
114,6,"whether he be from the jinn or humans.” {1}",footnotes:1:According to some scholars
